=C2=A0Great question! H=
oping you don't mind, I am forwarding this reply to vedic-wisdom yahoogroup=
.=C2=A0Yes, Sri Krishna did advise following swadharma (one's own dharma) a=
t the beginning of Bhagavad Gita. But he also said in the last
 chapter "Ro=
undly give up all dharmas and surrender unto Me". When Bhairavashtakam says=
 "swadharma maarga naashakam", it is getting at the same idea!=C2=A0Based o=
n who we are, our background, our deep desires and debts from the past (whi=
ch we may not even remember now), and our current skills and resources, we =
all have our own personal (individual) dharmas (duties). We must fulfill th=
ose.=C2=A0But performing swadharma is the start of sadhana. Eventually, one=
 should be able to perform swadharma without attachment to its fruits and l=
ater without even the sense of doership! Then comes a stage when one is not=
 even attached to the idea that "this is my dharma. I must do this". Whatev=
er Nature has placed one in a position to do, one does it detachedly, with =
neither sadness/disappointment nor with happiness/excitement, but with the =
spirit of "this is what Supreme Lord is doing through me at this instant". =
One overcomes the notions that "I am so and so. I need to do so
 and so", g=
ives up one's own will and flows like a light leaf in the wind of samsara. =
Wherever one flows and whatever objects one touches, one sees it as the wil=
l of Supreme Lord and has no notions of one's own will or one's own duties.=
 That is the state of liberated enlightenment.
=C2=A0Bhairava is extolled i=
n Bhairavashtakam as the one who brings that state. Krishna also teaches to=
 get to that state, but he does so in the last chapter of Bhagavad Gita. Be=
fore you get there, however, you may have to follow the instructions in pre=
vious chapters!=C2=A0A lot of modern Hindu philosophy taught by many modern=
 gurus, especially of the Vedantic bent, is based on the final target rathe=
r than the path(s) one needs to walk, to get to the target. It assumes that=
 you are already close to the target. It ends up misleading and creating wr=
ong notions in unprepared sadhakas like "all is delusion", "everything is t=
he same", "what you do does not matter". The greatness of Bhagavad Gita is =
that it talks about the path(s) as well as the target and has something rel=
evant to everyone.
=C2=A0
Best regards,
